    null,   // 504
    "{vet} came in the night the whole sprawl was calling for {vet}'s head, and asked me, of all people, if there was still a line. Back in {home} we'd have called that a confession.",   // 505
    "{vet} finally said out loud what {vet} was afraid of, and it wasn't the army coming for {vet}. It was the people signing the checks. I've been afraid of those people for {vet} ever since.",   // 506
    "{vet} told me about beating the people upstairs and I waited for the part where it felt like a victory. It never came. I stopped waiting for {vet}'s wins to sound like wins.",   // 507
    "{vet} confused a corporate threat with the oldest hurt {vet} carries, and for one minute at that counter let me see both at once. I finally understood the war was never the worst thing done to {vet}.",   // 508
    "{vet} won the final battle of a war that someone upstream had already sold out from under {vet}. I watched {vet} understand it at my table, and there was nothing to win back to {home} with anymore.",   // 509
    "{vet} crossed a dead sea and chose to remember the two things {vet} got back instead of the eight {vet} destroyed. That's the most like the kid from {home} {vet} has sounded since shipping out.",   // 510
    "{vet} came back from a light that erased a whole army with one name to save, and we held the only funeral {fallen} will ever get over two cold bowls. {vet} has a home in {home} for as long as I'm breathing. The wall can keep the rest.",   // 511
    "{vet} survived because someone spent their last breath on {vet}, and came to my counter not knowing if that was a debt or a gift. I made {vet} eat. It's the only debt I know how to forgive at this table.",   // 512
    "{vet} sat across from me weighing whether to spend everything on a chance to pull one dead name back, and I watched {vet} realize the company had even put a price on grief. I told {vet} to keep {fallen} off their books. Some things you don't lease back.",   // 513
    "{vet} could've spent everything trying to buy a dead name back, and instead told me what {vet} wanted to live for. I covered the ad with my hand and told {vet} to chase that home. That was the first time the war wasn't running {vet}'s mouth.",   // 514
    "{vet} came in cut by a blade fast as a rumor and told me there's a man out in the sprawl A&O already paid to finish {vet}. Every bowl I set down now I wonder if it's the last. {vet} should be home in {home}, not waiting on a contractor.",   // 515
    "{vet} won a duel nobody else walked away from and called it the worst trade of {vet}'s life. I turned {vet}'s cut arm to the light and told {vet} to make {fallen} have meant something. It's the only medicine I've got at this counter.",   // 516
    "{vet} finally told me the truth about how {home} kept its lights through the lean years, and it wasn't clean. I kept the secret the way I kept the lights. Family doesn't audit family.",   // 517
    "{vet} earns in money I can't spend and came to tell me the only thing it bought that mattered was sitting across from me. We split one bowl on it. Some things the company never figured out how to charge for.",   // 518
    "{vet} told me the company that erased {vet}'s war now owns the wall {vet}'s dead are nailed to and rents grief by the visit. I turned their photo face-down on my own table. {fallen} got mourned on free ground that night. {vet} can always come home in {home} to mourn the rest.",   // 519
    "{vet} had been holding {fallen}'s name in like saying it would make the death true, and let it go at my counter at last. I took {vet}'s hand. We made {fallen} permanent together, off the company's wall and on our own. That's what {home} is for.",   // 520
