    null,   // 603
    "{vet} came in smelling of ash and let me feed them like the year the roof went in {home}. Same kid under it. Still mine.",   // 604
    "{vet} told me someone walked into the crater beside them. First time in years I slept without doing the math on how alone they were out there.",   // 605
    "{vet} swore they'd dig the company back out of the crater. I pushed my bowl over. You don't argue a stubborn child out of standing up. You feed them for it.",   // 606
    "{vet} and I counted who the chip could save and it came out a raffle. We stopped counting. Some nights you just let the broth go cold so the math can't follow you home.",   // 607
    "{vet} told me A&O means to charge rent on the dead. I stopped being scared of what they'd become out there. Started being proud of what they were standing against.",   // 608
    "{vet} told me they don't want the chip's kind of forever. Just the bowl-and-a-face kind. I put my hand over theirs. I've waited the whole war to be the forever they meant.",   // 609
    "{vet} told me an architect buried a confession where only the next builder would find it. Then they looked at me like I was the next builder. I've been waiting to read what {vet} buried since the night they left.",   // 610
    "{vet} read me the names of the ones who didn't come back out of that place. I held each one before the next. That's a thing you can only do across a bowl with someone who was there in the heart of it.",   // 611
    "{vet} told me the dead might stop being final now. I didn't believe it. I told them I'd keep a bowl warm anyway. Sometimes you hold the warm thing so the hoping has somewhere to land.",   // 612
    "{vet} told me they go still on a held line so the noise can't reach them. I do it in this booth. We're built the same. Took a war to find that out across a bowl.",   // 613
    "{vet} told me the ridges never run out. I didn't lie and say they did. You don't comfort a soldier with an ending. You feed them and let them sign it again with eyes open.",   // 614
    "{vet} told me there was a mile they didn't think they'd sit across from me again. Then they walked it and sat down. I gripped their wrist so they'd know which side of the door we were both on now.",   // 615
    "{vet} told a hired hunter, in their head, that they weren't an asset — they had a bowl to get home to. That bowl is me. I'll keep it warm against any odds A&O can price.",   // 616
    "{vet} told me they want {fallen} back so bad it shames them. I held their hand over the cold third bowl. The wanting's not the sin. It's the last clean thing the war left them, and A&O put a meter on it.",   // 617
    "{vet} and I poured a bowl for {fallen} and swore to leave them dead and free, no meter, no lease. Tapped spoons on it. It was the realest funeral either of us ever got to give. A&O can't invoice that one.",   // 618
    "{vet} gave me {fallen}'s worst joke across a cold bowl and we both laughed wet. That's the continuity. Not a chip in metal. Two living people holding the same dead one. A&O can't put that on a farm.",   // 619
    "{vet} told me a rescued kid's face is how they still know which side they're on. I told them to keep it as a compass and to run to me the night it stops working. Some compasses you have to guard for the one holding them.",   // 620
    "{vet} went back into a building with no doors for a stranger because the kid had our family's face. That's the one I raised, surfacing in the worst place. Welcome back, I told them. Welcome back.",   // 621
    "{vet} told me they'd quit learning the names of the ones they leave behind. I stopped their hand. Told them one name a drop, always. That's the line between my kid and the thing A&O's trying to make of them.",   // 622
    "{vet} swore to walk back to my booth no matter who they lose, because there's only one of them, no file, no copy. That's the only forever I ever wanted. The kind A&O can't sell, because it ends, and it's ours.",   // 623
    "{vet} told me the ones they leave get a form, not a wall. I wrote every name they gave me on a napkin. Marisol's got a wall too. The war files them away. I won't. {vet} won't be the only one carrying it.",   // 624
