    "{vet} can raise the dead now and still can't come back to {home} alive. I don't know which fact frightens me more.",   // 713
    "{vet} carries a wall of the dead so the company can't call them numbers. Someone should carry {vet}.",   // 714
    "{vet} marches toward a tower that keeps death and still won't take the road back to {home}. The faith's pointed the wrong way.",   // 715
    "The war is teaching {vet} the company's words. I keep the old ones from {home} warm in case {vet} ever wants them back.",   // 716
    "If A&O ever backs {vet} up, I'll let the subscription lapse. {home} doesn't keep people in refrigerators. It buries them and remembers.",   // 717
    "{vet} spends everything to exist one more quarter. I'm just saving a stool so there's something here when the quarter ends.",   // 718
    "{vet} grieves {fallen} by missing them in a war. I grieve {vet} by setting a bowl out in {home} and pretending the war is a long shift.",   // 719
    "{vet} fought a five-story machine and the people who own it kept their lunch reservation. I want {vet} out before the hand behind the hammer learns {vet}'s name.",   // 720
    "{vet} could've become the man foreclosing the dead. Came back to {home}'s booth instead. I hold {vet} to the small difference that's left.",   // 721
    "{vet} keeps deciding there's nothing left to lose. I keep being the thing across the table that proves the audit wrong.",   // 722
    "{vet} thinks leaving {home} was a layoff. It wasn't. The door stays unlocked, no severance, no clause — just {vet}'s old seat.",   // 723
    "{vet} sets the extra place for the company's discards now — same as we did in {home} for whoever showed up hungry. The war didn't take everything.",   // 724
    "{vet} carries a wall of the dead that's now a wall of choices. I can't take the wall. I can keep a warm bowl in {home} for the nights it gets too heavy.",   // 725
    "{vet} triages the dead now and hates the pen. I'd rather it be {vet}'s steady hand than a stranger's. Still wish {vet} never had to hold it.",   // 726
    "{vet} said the whole thing at last, the night before the worst fight, and meant it. Whatever the war keeps, it can't have that. The porch light in {home} stays on.",   // 727
    "{vet} made me swear not to buy {vet} back from the company. If the wall takes {vet}, {home} will keep the real face. No subscription. No cold body. A promise.",   // 728
